<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Distinguished by the sericeous stem, short obtuse sepals, small, lobed corolla and tendency to have short rigid peduncles giving the plant a characteristic intricate habit.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
The recently described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. R. Mill" authorityYear="2013" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus excelsus" order="Solanales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="excelsus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Convolvulus excelsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Saudi Arabia is distinguished principally by its tall habit and disjunct distribution. However neither its height nor its disjunction is as distinctive as 
<bibRefCitation author="Mill, RR" journalOrPublisher="Kaiserliche Akademie der Wissenschaften, St. Petersburg" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="367 - 379" publicationUrl="10.1017/S0960428613000048" refId="B232" refString="Mill, RR, 2013. New taxa of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae) from the Arabian Peninsula. In: Edinburgh Journal of Botany.: 367 - 379, DOI: 10.1017/S0960428613000048" title="New taxa of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae) from the Arabian Peninsula." url="10.1017/S0960428613000048" volumeTitle="Edinburgh Journal of Botany." year="2013">Mill (2013)</bibRefCitation>
suggests, there being records from scattered locations in many countries (see above) and images and descriptions of specimens at least 1 m high.
</paragraph>
